Anonymous Thu 15 Dec 2022 23:06:48 No.53049862 Report
Quoted By: >>53050466
>>53049387
The tradition, and it feels really weird to use that word here, for short fiction on 4chins is second person greentext. I personally dislike it. It's an cramped, uncomfortable, extremely contrived form of constrained writing that seems to have been created as a work-around for imageboards with two thousand character post limits. I believe that good prose stays out of the way and lets the reader see the story. Second person greentext is extremely noticeable and for me tends to break immersion. That having been said, I do use it for anonymous funposting here. If I were going to create anything to put anywhere else at all, it'd be in a much more conventional, much less obtrusive form. I favor third person subjective viewpoint where we see the character's inner monologue and perceptions. I think it's most natural for most types of stories.

Anonymous Fri 16 Dec 2022 07:31:27 No.53058306 Report
Quoted By: >>53061849
>>53057874
Cathouse is seriously weird and I am boggled that Niven signed off on it, or maybe he'd signed away the rights to this point. It involves a human and several aliens of a species Niven came up with, the Kzinti. They have DNA--one of the bits of worldbuilding in the original stories going back to the 1960s was that a couple billion years back, a starfaring species accidentally left sewage and bits of leftover genetically engineered food yeast on a bunch of planets, and on some of them evolution took place over the interval between then and now. The Kzinti are generally described in his stories as ugly hulking brutes combining everything that is alarming and wrong to human perception about rats and tigers, but the resemblance is strictly coincidental and other than being bipedal, bifurcated, and bilaterally symmetrical, they have little in common with any species that evolved on Earth. They are, technically, mammals, but they're not even vertebrates. They are the apex predators of an arid, high-gravity death world. They are as intelligent as humans but much more bound by instinct, and their brains are hardwired to see every other living thing in the galaxy as slaves and/or food.

Cathouse is about a human guy shipwrecked on a planet where he finds some female Kzinti and makes friends with them. He is 80% of the way to wanting to fuck one of them when other stuff happens (like the old pulp authors said, when you can't figure out what to do next, drop a corpse through the skylight) and the interspecies romance subplot goes off the rails.

This is really, really not in keeping with the nature of the Kzinti as Niven conceived of them. In 1992 Niven threatened to sue a furry erotica author named Elf Sternberg for writing stories of humans and Kzinti fucking and posting them on the Internet.
